summary:
The `SwitchboardError` class in this code serves as a wrapper for handling errors in the `sbv2-solana` project. It provides a convenient way to convert numerical error codes into more descriptive `SwitchboardError` objects based on the program Interface Definition Language (IDL).

The main functionality of this class is provided by the `fromCode` static method. This method takes a `SwitchboardProgram` object and a numerical error code as input arguments. It then iterates through the errors specified in the program IDL and checks if the provided error code matches any of the error codes in the IDL. If a match is found, a new `SwitchboardError` object is created and returned with the corresponding error information. If no match is found, an error is thrown indicating that the error code could not be found.

The `SwitchboardError` class also contains four readonly properties: `program`, `name`, `code`, and `msg`. The `program` property holds a reference to the `SwitchboardProgram` object containing the program IDL. The `name` property is a string representing the error type, while the `code` property is the numerical representation of the error. The `msg` property is an optional string that provides a detailed description of the error.

Here's an example of how the `SwitchboardError` class might be used in the larger project:

```javascript
try {
  // Some code that may throw a numerical error code
} catch (errorCode) {
  const switchboardError = SwitchboardError.fromCode(switchboardProgram, errorCode);
  console.error(`Error: ${switchboardError.name} (${switchboardError.code}): ${switchboardError.msg}`);
}
```

In this example, if an error occurs, the numerical error code is caught and converted into a `SwitchboardError` object using the `fromCode` method. The error information is then logged to the console in a more human-readable format.
